<p><i><b>Foucault's Pendulum</b></i> (original title: <i>Il pendolo di Foucault</i>) is a <a href="/wiki/Novel" title="Novel">novel</a> by <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Novelist" title="Novelist" class="mw-redirect">novelist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a> <a href="/wiki/Umberto_Eco" title="Umberto Eco">Umberto Eco</a>. It was first published in 1988; the translation into English by <a href="/wiki/William_Weaver" title="William Weaver">William Weaver</a> appeared a year later.</p>
<p><i>Foucault's Pendulum</i> is divided into ten segments represented by the ten <a href="/wiki/Sephirot" title="Sephirot">Sefiroth</a>. The novel is full of <a href="/wiki/Esoteric" title="Esoteric" class="mw-redirect">esoteric</a> references to the <a href="/wiki/Kabbalah" title="Kabbalah">Kabbalah</a>, <a href="/wiki/Alchemy" title="Alchemy">alchemy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Conspiracy_theory" title="Conspiracy theory">conspiracy theory</a>, so many that critic and novelist <a href="/wiki/Anthony_Burgess" title="Anthony Burgess">Anthony Burgess</a> suggested that it needed an index. The title of the book derives from <a href="/wiki/Foucault_pendulum" title="Foucault pendulum">an actual pendulum</a> designed by the French physicist <a href="/wiki/L%C3%A9on_Foucault" title="Léon Foucault">Léon Foucault</a> to demonstrate the rotation of the earth.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
